Did you know that 4.4 million potatoes go to waste every day in the UK? Inspired by @hellmannsuk and @channel4 show #CookCleverLessWaste I decided to use my leftover potatoes to make my simple, easy Crispy Smashed Potatoes recipe. Trust me, you’ll never waste a single potato ever again! 
 
Now, this isn't my typical IG reel recipe video, so watch this video all the way to the end to see how to make this incredibly easy dish!
 
Serves 4 as a side, or 2 as a main
 
15-20 baby potatoes
1-2 tbsp Hellmann's Vegan Mayo
1 tsp smoked paprika
1/4 lemon, juiced
1/2 tsp salt
1/4 tsp black pepper
Pickled red onions
Fresh dill
Fresh chives
Extra virgin olive oil
 
* Bring the water in a saucepan to a boil. Add salt to the water then carefully drop the baby potatoes in the salted boiling water. Cook the potatoes for 15-20 minutes until soft then drain.
* Meanwhile, preheat the oven to 200C.
* Gently press the potatoes until the peel breaks and place them on a baking sheet. Drizzle a bit of oil, a pinch of salt and black pepper and bake for 20 minutes until golden and crispy.
* In the almost empty jar of Hellmann's vegan mayo, add the smoked paprika in lemon juice and shake for a few seconds until the ingredients are mixed well. Add a few dollops of the smoked lemon mayo to the potatoes, add the pickled red onions and fresh herbs. 
 
Enjoy! 
 
To get started your food waste journey, check our Hellmann’s Food Waste Handbook here - https://www.hellmanns.com/uk/secure/signup.html
 
What’s more, as part of @hellmannsuk fight against food waste, Hellmann's has donated an equivalent of 40,000 meals to a charitable food redistributor @fareshareuk. 
 
#HellmannsUK #CookCleverLessWaste #MakeTasteNotWaste #Ad

AD  Live Q&A with @tetrapak (20 minutes)⁣
 ⁣
From the role of packaging to reducing food waste and the environment, I have a quick chat with Tetra Pak's Director of Business Insights & Analytics to understand how Tetra Pak's is improving the world of packaging solutions.⁣
 ⁣
Covid-19 has displaced the environment as the number one consumer concern. Food safety and food security have risen significantly as a result, and trying to balance these concerns with our worries for the environment are creating a dilemma.⁣
 ⁣
Health is now connected to heightened issues of food safety and hygiene; two-thirds of consumers said that being healthy is being safe. Improving food safety was cited as the number one priority for manufacturers. ⁣
 ⁣
Transparency is key, with almost three in five consumers saying they want to know all they can about product production.⁣
 ⁣
Anything we didn’t cover? Let me know what you would ask Tetra Pak in the comments below.⁣
 ⁣
@TetraPak #TetraPakIndex

node.title: Live Q&A in conversation with Tetra Pak

in collaboration with @SmartEnergyGB and @homebase_uk. There are tons of ways to make your home super green and more efficient, from getting a smart meter installed to monitor and reduce your energy use through to wasting less food.⁣
⁣
✅My 3 super green recipes today have been inspired by Homebase’s new Green Aisle in collaboration with Smart Energy GB, where you can find a whole host of sustainable home improvement products, as well as information on smart meters.⁣
⁣
Leftover Spinach Tortillas⁣
240g flour⁣
1 tsp salt⁣
90-100ml water⁣
⁣
Leftover Herb Hummus⁣
1 tin of chickpeas, reserve chickpea water⁣
A handful of mixed herbs⁣
2 tbsp olive oil⁣
1/2 lemon, juiced⁣
1 tsp salt⁣
1/2 tsp black pepper⁣
1 tbsp tahini⁣
Splash of chickpea water⁣
⁣
Green Doughnuts⁣
A handful of leftover spinach⁣
200g flour⁣
80g sugar⁣
1 tsp baking powder⁣
1/4 tsp salt⁣
180ml plant-based milk⁣
60ml chickpea water⁣
2 tbsp apple sauce ⁣
1 tsp vanilla extract⁣
⁣
Hope you enjoyed my 3 super green recipes, and also do make sure to visit The Green Aisle at a Homebase store near you! #TheGreenAisle⁣

Here’s a snippet from last week‘s conversation with @mileycyrus on her @instagram live show. ⁣
⁣

⁣

⁣

One Pot 🍋 Pasta 

Super simple, easy, minimal ingredients and it’s ONE POT which means less washing up!

Save it
Share it
Cook it

Serves 2
300g rigatoni
1 onion, diced
3 garlic cloves, chopped
240ml hot water
(400g)1 tin full-fat coconut milk 
1 lemon, juice and zest
1-2 tbsp olive oil
Salt
Black pepper
Red chilli flakes

1️⃣ sauté onions in a frying pan for 5-7 minutes. 
2️⃣ add garlic and stir for 1 minute.
3️⃣ add the remaining ingredients and cook on a medium high heat for 15 minutes - occasionally stirring.

Serve with leafy greens and/or herbs

🔥new kitchen, new recipe🔥

👨🏻‍🍳my first time cooking in my brand new kitchen! do you like it? 

let’s make my crispy baked mushroom noodles

a few mushrooms were going spare and didn’t want anything to go to waste — mushrooms always go well with noodles, so here it is!

100g noodles
80g mushrooms
30g toasted mixed nuts
30g cucumber
2 tsp soy sauce
2 tsp sesame oil
2 tsp brown sugar
spring onions
fresh coriander
crushed chilli

peanut sauce:
2 tbsp peanut butter
1 tbsp soy sauce
2 tsp sesame oil
1/2 tsp brown rice vinegar
Splash of water

*Bake mushrooms at 200C for 12-15 minutes until crispy.

You💯% need to make this. 

Takes less than 30 minutes
Satisfying and delicious

Let’s make my easy chickpea coconut curry

Serves 2-4
Cook time 25 minutes

300g cooked chickpeas
1 onion, diced
1-2 tbsp coriander stems, chopped
4 garlic cloves, chopped
1 red bell pepper, sliced
130g carrots, chopped
25g ginger, grated
400g coconut milk
1/2 tsp turmeric powder
1 tsp cumin powder
1/4 tsp red chili flakes
1 tsp garam masala
Pinch of salt 
Black pepper
Fresh coriander
Lime juice
Red onion, thinly sliced

1️⃣Heat oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Stir in onion, coriander stems and bay leaf. Cook, stirring occasionally, until onion is golden on the edges, about 5-10 minutes.
2️⃣Add garlic and ginger; cook until fragrant, about 2 minutes, stirring frequently. 
3️⃣Stir in chickpeas and red bell pepper, about 2 minutes, occasionally stirring. Stir in turmeric powder, ground cumin, red chili flakes, garam masala, salt and black pepper; cook for an additional 30-45 seconds. Stir in the coconut milk and add the carrot. Bring to a simmer and continue to simmer for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally. 
4️⃣Serve over rice, couscous, quinoa or noodles, if you like, and top with cilantro, thinly sliced red onions, and a squeeze of lime juice.

Chickpea ‘TUNA’

🤳🏼Tag and show me your chickpea ‘tuna’ (recipe below).

Super easy and versatile. You can add or sub any veg you have in your fridge. It’s that simple!

The key is smashing the cooked chickpeas, adding the vegan mayo and if you have it, add the nori. This combo is what you need for a delicious fake ‘tuna’.

Here’s how you make it:
400g cooked chickpeas
1/2 red onion, diced
2 celery stalks, sliced
2 tbsp vegan mayo
1/2 tsp cayenne 
1 lemon, juice and zest
Pinch of salt
Black pepper
1 nori sheet, optional

1️⃣smash 3/4 of the chickpeas in a bowl.
2️⃣add the remaining ingredients and mix
3️⃣serve by itself, in a wrap or sandwich

Did you know that 4.4 million potatoes go to waste every day in the UK? Inspired by @hellmannsuk and @channel4 show #CookCleverLessWaste I decided to use my leftover potatoes to make my simple, easy Crispy Smashed Potatoes recipe. Trust me, you’ll never waste a single potato ever again! 
 
Now, this isn't my typical IG reel recipe video, so watch this video all the way to the end to see how to make this incredibly easy dish!
 
Serves 4 as a side, or 2 as a main
 
15-20 baby potatoes
1-2 tbsp Hellmann's Vegan Mayo
1 tsp smoked paprika
1/4 lemon, juiced
1/2 tsp salt
1/4 tsp black pepper
Pickled red onions
Fresh dill
Fresh chives
Extra virgin olive oil
 
* Bring the water in a saucepan to a boil. Add salt to the water then carefully drop the baby potatoes in the salted boiling water. Cook the potatoes for 15-20 minutes until soft then drain.
* Meanwhile, preheat the oven to 200C.
* Gently press the potatoes until the peel breaks and place them on a baking sheet. Drizzle a bit of oil, a pinch of salt and black pepper and bake for 20 minutes until golden and crispy.
* In the almost empty jar of Hellmann's vegan mayo, add the smoked paprika in lemon juice and shake for a few seconds until the ingredients are mixed well. Add a few dollops of the smoked lemon mayo to the potatoes, add the pickled red onions and fresh herbs. 
 
Enjoy! 
 
To get started your food waste journey, check our Hellmann’s Food Waste Handbook here - https://www.hellmanns.com/uk/secure/signup.html
 
What’s more, as part of @hellmannsuk fight against food waste, Hellmann's has donated an equivalent of 40,000 meals to a charitable food redistributor @fareshareuk.

Bunch of carrot tops, washed and rinsed
1 tbsp olive oil
4 roasted garlic cloves
1 tbsp white miso (optional)
2 tbsp nutritional yeast
2 tbsp toasted sunflower seeds
50ml cooked pasta water
Juice of half a lemon
Pinch of salt
Black pepper 

Blend all ingredients until smooth. Add to your favourite pasta for a quick and easy lunch/dinner.

Save leftovers in a clean jar and by adding a thin layer of olive oil on top.

Here’s how I make my cauliflower …

❤️Save this recipe for when you need inspiration. 

Now you’ll never throw away cauliflower leaves again! #nowaste 

Serves:
4 as a side, 2 as a mains

1 large cauliflower, remove florets, leaves and core
1-2 tbsp olive oil
2-3 tbsp cornflour or cornstarch
Salt
Black pepper

Tahini Mustard Lemon Sauce:
1 tbsp tahini
2 tsp dijon mustard
1/4 lemon, juice
1 tsp maple syrup

Preheat oven at 200C or 390F

Add the cauliflower, leaves and the core to a large mixing bowl. Pour the olive oil and mix. Next, add the cornflour, salt and black pepper and mix again. 

Spread on a baking sheet evenly and bake for 15-20 minutes until the cauliflower is cooked and the edges begin to brown.

Meanwhile, to make the sauce, add all the ingredients to a empty jam jar or bowl, shake or whisk until smooth.

Add the baked cauliflower and leaves to a bowl, drizzle the tahini mustard lemon sauce and mix well. 

To serve, add cauliflower to a plate or bowl, sprinkle a bit of sesame seeds and chives. 

You can have this by itself, next to any dish or incorporated into tacos, pasta and rice dishes.

Enjoy!

It’s like a risotto, but it’s not…

🕺🏻Need dinner inspiration or a new staple dish for the week? 
This dish comes all the bases. 

It’s creamy and garlicky!
Swap any veg in season and finish with fresh herbs and lemon.

😁You’re going to like this dish!

Here’s how to make it…

Serves 4
1 shallot, diced
4 garlic loves, thinly sliced
225g brown rice
250g mushrooms, sliced - don’t remove the stems
560ml plant-based milk (I prefer oat milk)
100g spring peas, fresh or frozen 
125g asparagus, roughly chopped
2 tbsp cornflour
2 tbsp nutritional yeast
Salt + black pepper
Fresh parsley, stems roughly chopped

In a frying pan on medium heat, add 2 tbsp of olive oiled heat until warm. Next, add the shallot (or onion) and sauté for 5-10 minutes until soft and translucent. Then add the cornflour - stir to incorporate with the shallot, still stirring, add half of the plant-based milk.

Once the sauce thickens add the remaining plant-based milk, nutritional yeast, a generous pinch of salt and black pepper - season to your liking. Cook on a low heat occasionally stirring for 3-5 minutes. Remove from heat and let the sauce sit. 
 Meanwhile, in a separate frying pan add some oil. When the oil is warm add the garlic and fry for 60 seconds or until the garlic begins to brown lightly. Next, add the mushrooms and stir for 5 minutes until the mushrooms reduce in size. Add the spring peas, asparagus, parsley stems, lemon zest and juice and sauté for 5-10 minutes.

Bring the sauce to a low heat then add the cooked rice and sautéed veg, and stir. 

Add a few spoonfuls to a plate or bowl, garnish with fresh parsley, a pinch of salt and squeeze of lemon. 

Enjoy!

This is my tomato sauce🍝

😬If there’s one recipe I’m nervous to share with you, it’s this one! 

👵🏼There are so many ways to make a tomato sauce and my sauce may not be what your grandmother would approve of, but it is truly delicious...

👨🏻‍🍳Here’s how to make it...

2 x 400g tinned chopped tomatoes
1 onion, finely diced
4 garlic cloves, sliced
3 tbsp tomato paste
1 tsp salt
1/2 tsp black pepper
1 tsp dried oregano
1/2 tsp dried parsley
1/2 tsp dried thyme
2 tbsp olive oil
1/2 tsp sugar (optional)

Add the olive oil into a saucepan on medium heat. Once the oil is warm add the onion and sauté for 5-10 minutes until soft. Add the garlic and stir for 1-2 minutes.

Once the onion and garlic are ready, add the tomato paste, stir and cook for one minute before adding the seasoning. The tomato paste should thicken as you stir and incorporate with the onion and garlic.

Next, add the chopped tomatoes, stir for a few minutes and bring to a simmer - you may want to add a splash (2 tbsp of water). Let the sauce to simmer for 5 minutes, then reduce heat stir occasionally, cooking the sauce on a low heat for 20 minutes before serving. 

Serve the tomato sauce with your favourite pasta. It’s freezer friendly up to 1 month and even better the next day. Keep in fridge for up to 5-7 days in a clean, sealed container.

I hope you like my tomato sauce!

No-waste Beefless & Broccoli Stir-fry using The @unbelievablealt 
 
I don't normally go for meat-free alternatives, but this is by far one of the most delicious meat-free products out in stores now! @unbelievablealt means eating a flexitarian diet doesn’t need to be difficult! Cutting down on meat has a reduced impact on the environment, with their meat alternatives emitting 50-80% less CO2 into the atmosphere.
 
I was meant to meet @djbbq for The Unbelievable ALT. Meat Free Meet Up series, but due to COVID safety, I was left alone in my small kitchen to make an incredibly simple, yet delicious dish.

1 pack of The Unbelievable ALT. Tender Beefless Pieces
1 broccoli, separate floret and grated stem
125g soba noodles (or any noodle of your choice)
1 onion, sliced
4 garlic cloves, minced
1 tbsp fresh ginger, grated
1 carrot, julienned

Sauce:
2 tbsp soy sauce or tamari
2 tsp sesame oil
1 tsp rice vinegar
1/2 tsp maple syrup
1 tbsp peanut butter
1/2 tsp red chilli flakes

To a frying pan on medium heat, add 1-2 tbsp of neutral oil - I prefer sunflower oil. Sauté the onion for 3 minutes until soft then add the garlic, ginger and cook for another 2 minutes until fragrant. 
 
Add the grated broccoli stem and The Unbelievable ALT. Tender Beefless Pieces and cook for roughly 8 minutes. Meanwhile, in a large saucepan of boiling water, cook the noodles according to the packet's instructions. For the last 2-3 minutes of cooking, add the broccoli florets. Remove from heat and drain.
 
Add the noodles and broccoli florets to the frying pan, remove from heat and stir whilst combining the sauce. For the last minute, add the carrots and combine. 
 
To serve, add the stir-fry to a plate or bowl and add your favourite toppings, from toasted sesame seeds to fresh coriander. 
 
Enjoy!

🌮🌮Crispy Jackfruit Tacos🌮🌮

Super easy and simple to make, you’re going to love it. 

When cooked, jackfruit has a very similar texture to pulled pork or shredded chicken. I don’t think a meat-eater would really notice the difference, but maybe I’m wrong!

👨🏻‍🍳Here’s how to make it…

400g tinned jackfruit, drained and rinsed (king oyster mushrooms, optional)
1/2 onion, diced
3 garlic cloves, diced
1 tsp coriander/cilantro stems, chopped
2 tsp cumin
1/2 tsp paprika
1 tsp tomato paste
2 tsp adobo sauce (optional)
1 tbsp tamari or soy sauce
1 tsp maple syrup

Avocado sauce:
1/2 ripe avocado
Handful of fresh coriander/ cilantro
3 spring onions, roughly chopped
1 tbsp chives, chopped
2 tbsp water
1/2 lime juice
Salt
Black pepper
—
*If omitting the adobo sauce then add 1 tbsp of tomato paste instead.
—
Pre-heat oven to 200C/390F

In a frying pan on medium heat add some oil and sauté the onions and garlic for 5-10 minutes until soft. 

Next, add the spices and stir for another 1-2 minutes before adding the jackfruit. Cook on medium heat for a further 5 minutes. 

Transfer the mixture to a greased baking sheet and bake for 10-12 minutes until crispy around the edges. 

Serve the crispy baked jackfruit on a tortilla with my avocado sauce, pickled red onion and fresh coriander/ cilantro. 

Other options: Serve with rice and sautéed veg, in a burrito or with pasta.
